<HEAD>With Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Flyby Allows Photos of Moon's Far Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists say pictures of the far side
of the moon taken by the spacecraft <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> will help fill a blank
spot on the map of the planet.
   The pictures, taken as <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> sped past the moon and <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> on
its six-year voyage to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, also should reveal more about the
mineral content of the moon's crust, scientists said <DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   ``We're actually doing some new observation,'' said <PERSON>James Head</PERSON>,
a member of <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s imaging team at <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s Jet Propulsion
Laboratory.
   The <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION> displayed
black and white photos of the full moon that provided a sharp image
of the <LOCATION>Orientale Basin</LOCATION> as well as portions of both the near and far
sides of the moon.
   The spacecraft swung into the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s gravitational field
<DATE>Saturday</DATE>, hurtling 597 miles above the western <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> at the
point of its closest approach.
   By sweeping near <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> was able to use gravitational
pull like a slingshot to increase its speed by 11,600 mph, boosting
its velocity to 79,000 mph in relation to the sun.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s approach allowed scientists to focus the craft's
cameras on the far side of the moon for the first exploration of
the region since <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s Apollo missions in the <DATE>1970s</DATE>.
   The cameras photographed a wedge of moonscape near the south
pole on the far side that somehow was missed by previous <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and
Soviet mapping missions, said project scientist <PERSON>Torrence Johnson</PERSON>.
   ``That's interesting, it's got craters just like the rest of the
moon, but there's no great scientific surprise in that,'' <PERSON>Johnson</PERSON>
said.
   A subsequent journey through the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s magnetic field gave
scientists their first measurements of a solar storm in which
magnetically charged ions take on higher energy levels.
   The data could reveal whether the majority of these ions, which
trigger colorful auroras near <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s magnetic poles, come from the
sun or <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, said <PERSON>Lou Frank</PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s magnetic field
working group.
</TEXT>
