<HEAD>Galileo Flyby Spurs NASA `Aliens' to Conclude There's Life on
Earth</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LA6, LA7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> scientists pretending to be
explorers from another world said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> they had concluded life
exists on <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, and it may be intelligent.
   The scientists based their conclusinon on data from the
Jupiter-bound <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> spacecraft.
   ``The accumulated evidence we have ... would give your
hypothetical explorer a very strong indication you had biological
activity on <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON>Torrence Johnson</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s chief
scientist at the <ORGANIZATION>Jet Propulsion Laboratory</ORGANIZATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s study of <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> illustrates how researchers use data
collected by spacecraft to reach conclusions about other planets.
   Galileo boomeranged past <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and the moon <DATE>Dec. 8</DATE>, using the
planet's gravity as a slingshot to speed it up and expand its orbit
around the sun so it can reach <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1995</DATE>.
   Scientists used the opportunity to treat Earth as an alien
planet, ordering <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> to snap a few thousand pictures and make
numerous measurements. They outlined their findings during a
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE> news conference.
   Measurements made by <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s infrared light-detecting
instrument showed <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s atmosphere is rich in nitrous oxide,
methane and oxygen, indicating ``there's a lot of life'' on the
planet, said laboratory scientist <PERSON>Robert W. Carlson</PERSON>.
   Another of <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s instruments picked up non-natural radio
signals that got stronger closer to the planet, which would make
alien scientists strongly suspect <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> has intelligent life that
makes radio broadcasts, <PERSON>Johnson</PERSON> said.
   The spaceship also detected lightning bolts, made measurements
to help explain creation of the <ORGANIZATION>Northern and Southern Lights</ORGANIZATION>,
determined the planet is warmed by a mild ``greenhouse effect'' and
detected a high-altitude ice cloud that helps cause the annual hole
in the protective ozone layer over <LOCATION>Antarctica</LOCATION>.
   On the moon, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> found evidence of a huge volcanic eruption
4 billion years ago. That shows such volcanic activity occurred
about 200 million years earlier than previously believed, said
<ORGANIZATION>Brown University</ORGANIZATION> geologist <PERSON>Jim Head</PERSON>.
   The spacecraft's pictures also confirmed the existence of a
1,200-mile-wide meteorite impact basin on the southern hemisphere
of the moon's far side, the largest such crater ever identified,
<PERSON>Head</PERSON> said.
   The <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION> released nine
more of <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s photos of the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and moon <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   One was a mosaic, assembled from 11 separate pictures, showing
all of icy <LOCATION>Antarctica</LOCATION>. Others showed huge lunar craters, a color
map of minerals on the moon's surface, clouds swirling over <LOCATION>South
America</LOCATION>, and <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION>'s larger lakes and Great Barrier Reef.
   The pictures didn't display evidence of life on <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> because
<ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s closest approach to the planet, at a distance of 597
miles, was over the southwest <LOCATION>Atlantic Ocean</LOCATION>. The detail in the
pictures was inadequate to reveal buildings, scientists said.
   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> also displayed two short movies, made by assembling
hundreds of <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s still photos, showing the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and moon
spinning.
   ``Top that, <PERSON>Ted Turner</PERSON>!'' Head declared after the colorized
lunar movie was played. He was referring to media mogul <PERSON>Turner</PERSON>'s
controversial practice of colorizing classic films.
   Also <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> fired its thrusters repeatedly to aim
itself properly for its close encounter with the asteroid Gaspra
next <DATE>Oct. 29</DATE>, said project manager <PERSON>Bill O'Neil</PERSON>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> will swing past <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> again <DATE>Dec. 8, 1992</DATE>, for a final
``gravity slingshot'' maneuver to help it reach <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>. In <DATE>July
1995</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> will separate into an orbiter and a probe. Both will
reach <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>December 1995</DATE>.
   The probe will descend into <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>'s atmosphere, returning data
to the orbiter until the probe is crushed by intense atmospheric
pressure. The orbiter will circle <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> for at least two years,
studying the planet and making closeup pictures of its 10 largest
moons.
</TEXT>
