<HEAD>NASA Adjusts Voyager 2's Trajectory To Neptune</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Voyager 2 spacecraft, flying through
space 2.6 billion miles from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, fired its thrusters <DATE>Friday</DATE> to
change course for its <DATE>August 1989</DATE> picture-taking encounter with the
planet <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> said.
   ``Responding to radio signals radioed from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, Voyager 2 fired
its hydrazine thrusters for three minutes and 29 seconds beginning
at <TIME>6:55 a.m. PST</TIME>,'' said a statement issued by the space agency's
Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
   Flight engineering manager <PERSON>Lanny Miller</PERSON> said radio signals sent
to <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> by the space probe indicated the maneuver succeeded.
   The pre-planned course correction will bring Voyager 2 some 6,200
miles closer to the solar system's eighth planet, but another major
maneuver next <DATE>April</DATE> and several subsequent but minor trajectory
changes will be required before the <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> flyby, said laboratory
spokeswoman <PERSON>Mary Beth Murrill</PERSON>.
   The spacecraft _ which passed by <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1979</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1981</DATE>
and Uranus in <DATE>1986</DATE> _ is scheduled to sweep within 3,000 miles of
<LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s cloud tops at <TIME>9 p.m. PDT</TIME> next <DATE>Aug. 24</DATE>, taking pictures
with its television camera.
   Five hours later, it will fly within 24,000 miles of <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s
moon <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION>, which scientists believe may have lakes of liquid
nitrogen.
   <PERSON>Murrill</PERSON> said Voyager 2 is 414.7 million miles from <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>, one
of the solar system's giant, gaseous outer planets.
   Radio commands to the probe and its response signals are
transmitted through large, dish-shaped radio antennae that make up
the Deep Space Network operated by the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and
Space Administration</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Goldstone</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Calif</LOCATION>.
   Voyager 2 is so far away that the signals take four hours to
reach it, even traveling at the speed of light.
   The <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> encounter will be the last of the so-called ``grand
tour'' of the outer planets by the Voyager probes. Voyagers 1 and 2
were launched from <LOCATION>Cape Canaveral</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Fla.</LOCATION>, in <DATE>1977</DATE>. Voyager 1, which
visited <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1979</DATE> and <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1980</DATE>, now is headed out of the
solar system.
   Scientists have called the Voyager mission humanity's most
productive space exploration effort because the two picture-taking
probes learned hundreds of times more about the outer planets than
all previous studies combined.
   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> scientists have said that by <DATE>1995</DATE>, when both probes are
searching for the edge of the solar system, the total cost of the
mission will be about <MONEY>$920 million</MONEY>, which is less than half what the
<ORGANIZATION>Pentagon</ORGANIZATION> spends during one workday.
   Among key Voyager discoveries were active volcanos spewing sulfur
on <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>'s moon Io, an icy volcanism that produced glacier-like
flows on some of the Saturnian and Uranian moons, and the discovery
of at least 17 previously unknown moons: three at <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, at least
four at <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> and 10 orbiting Uranus.
   The probes also discovered new rings encircling <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION>
and Uranus; orange smog and ethane-methane rain on <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION>'s moon
<ORGANIZATION>Titan</ORGANIZATION>, and dozens of giant hurricanes on <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
