<HEAD>Galileo Fires Thrusters as Part of Earth, Jupiter Missions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> spacecraft successfully
fired its thrusters almost 1,600 times during a four-day maneuver
designed to help it reach <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1995</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   The sequence of thruster pulses, completed late last <DATE>Thursday</DATE>,
slowed the spacecraft by about 55 mph, said <PERSON>Jim Wilson</PERSON>, a spokesman
for the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION>'s Jet
Propulsion Laboratory.
   The next set of maneuvers is scheduled for this <DATE>summer</DATE>, said <PERSON>Bob
MacMillin</PERSON> another spokesman.
   The 2.8-ton <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> was launched on its <MONEY>$1.35 billion</MONEY> mission by
the space shuttle Atlantis on <DATE>Oct. 18</DATE>.
   It flew past Venus on <DATE>Feb. 9</DATE> so that planet could act as a
``gravity slingshot'' to help propel the spacecraft on its looping
2.4-billion-mile, six-year journey to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, the solar system's
largest planet.
   The spacecraft will fly past <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> on <DATE>Dec. 8</DATE> of this year and
again on <DATE>Dec. 8, 1990</DATE>, in two more ``gravity slingshot'' maneuvers.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> will examine Earth, <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s moon and one or two
asteroids before the spacecraft separates into an orbiter and a
small probe in <DATE>July 1995</DATE>. In <DATE>December 1995</DATE>, they arrive at <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   There, the probe will parachute into the atmosphere and make
measurements until the planet's intense heat and pressure vaporize
it. The orbiter will photograph and study <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> and its major
moons until late <DATE>1997</DATE>, circling the planet instead of flying past
it like the Pioneer and Voyager spacecraft.
</TEXT>
