<HEAD>NASA: Photos Show Southern Lights On Neptune, Nitrogen In Triton
Atmosphere</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with evidence of broad dust bands
around planet. Picks up 6th grafs pvs, `Evidence for...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voyager 2, discovered broad, flat bands
of dust orbiting <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> and found evidence the planet has
``southern lights,'' <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> said <DATE>today</DATE>.
   The probe also detected nitrogen in the atmosphere of <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION>, the
moon whose pink snow and ice volcanoes were described by excited
scientists as unique in the solar system, <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> said.
   ``There's dust bands _ they're broad,'' said <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> astronomer <PERSON>Rich
Terrile</PERSON>, describing the findings from latest photorgraphs. The bands
orbit <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s equator, as do its narrow rings that were discovered
by Voyager earlier.
   Although Voyager has passed its closest encounters with <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>
and <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION>, it continued today to back recorded photographs taken
during the time of closest approach. And scientists and engineers
celebrated the spacecraft's successful flyby.
   ``My understanding was most of the engineers and science team had
one hell of a party <TIME>last night</TIME>,'' <PERSON>Mike Urban</PERSON>, a Voyager engineer,
said <DATE>today</DATE>.
   The one-ton space probe capped its historic 4.43-billion-mile,
12-year tour of four planets when it skimmed 3,048 miles over
<LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s north pole <DATE>Thursday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>, then dove past <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION>, the
planet's largest moon. It made its closest approach about 23,900
miles above the moon's surface at <TIME>2:10 a.m. PDT</TIME> <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   During its approach to <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>, Voyager discovered six moons
besides <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION> and Nereid, which were first observed from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. It
also discovered one complete ring of debris around the planet and a
partial ring, or ring arc, scientists believe will also prove to be
a complete ring.
   While only the narrow rings were visible as Voyager flew toward
<LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>, the broad dust bands became visible when they were backlit
by sunlight after the space probe passed the planet, <PERSON>Terrile</PERSON> said.
That makes them look like <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION>'s broad rings, but only when viewed
from behind <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>.
   The same thing happened when Voyager passed Uranus in <DATE>1986</DATE>. That
planet had 10 narrow rings when seen by the approaching spacecraft,
which then found extensive bands of dust after passing Uranus.
<PERSON>Terrile</PERSON> said <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s dust bands are not as extensive.
   Evidence for the glowing lights, known as an aurora, was found at
30 degrees south latitude on <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> as <ORGANIZATION>Voyager</ORGANIZATION>'s ultraviolet light
sensor made a north-to-south scan of the planet, deputy project
scientist <PERSON>Ellis Miner</PERSON> said <DATE>today</DATE>.
   Because the scan didn't cover different longitudes, scientists
don't know the aurora's full extent, or whether it circles <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>
east to west, as do <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s auroras, <PERSON>Miner</PERSON> said.
   Miner said <ORGANIZATION>Voyager</ORGANIZATION> also found nitrogen in <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION>'s atmosphere.
Nitrogen makes up <PERCENT>78 percent</PERCENT> of <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s atmosphere.
   On Earth, the northern and southern lights encircle the poles,
but can get pushed closer to the equator when the sun generates
magnetic storms. However, it would be very unusual for an aurora on
<LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> to get as close to the equator as 30 degrees latitude.
   Auroras are caused when electrically charged particles in the
solar wind spiral in toward a planet along magnetivc field lines. On
Earth they glow in visible light. Neptune's lights glow ultraviolet
because of hydrogen in its atmosphere.
   Engineers spent the night unloading Voyager's eight-track tape
recorder _ playing back pictures and scientific data recorded during
the <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION> rendezvous _ and also loaded new instructions
telling the probe how to point its cameras and sensors, <ORGANIZATION>Urban</ORGANIZATION> said.
   Voyager today started sending back its most detailed images of
<ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION>, which is four-fifth's the size of <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s moon. But pictures
returned <DATE>Friday</DATE> were more than enough to stun scientists.
   ``The range of geological forms is dazzling,'' astronomer-author
<PERSON>Carl Sagan</PERSON> said <DATE>Friday</DATE>. ``We are almost certainly in a regime of
volcanism involving ices, maybe exotic ices'' such as water ice
mixed with frozen nitrogen or methane (natural gas).
   The photographs show a cracked, frozen <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION> scarred by
thousand-foot-high ridges, fault lines, bowl-shaped craters,
mysterious domes and dark spots ringed with white halos that so far
defy explanation.
   ``The images returned this morning revealed a world unlike any
we've ever seen,'' Voyager project scientist <PERSON>Edward Stone</PERSON> said
<DATE>Friday</DATE> at the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION>'s Jet
Propulsion Laboratory.
   Icy volcanic flows have been seen on Uranus' moon <PERSON>Ariel</PERSON> and some
other moons, but <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION> is the first place scientists have actually
seen ice volcanoes, <ORGANIZATION>Stone</ORGANIZATION> said. Photographs showed at least three
inactive volcanoes.
   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> geologist <PERSON>Joseph Boyce</PERSON> said one of the ice volcanoes _ which
look like dry lakebeds filled with smooth material _ measures
several hundred miles across. Some were encircled with cliffs 1,000
to 2,000 feet high.
   The properties of exotic ices of water, methane and nitrogen
``are very different from ordinary ice,'' said <PERSON>Sagan</PERSON>, a member of
the Voyager imaging team. ``That may explain the exoticness of the
landforms.''
   Parts of the moon are frozen methane discolored by a bombardment
of radiation that produced chemical changes, <PERSON>Sagan</PERSON> said. ``We've got
pink snow. Think about how exotic that is.''
   Preliminary measurements of <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION>'s magnetic field suggest that
it does not have a north pole and a south pole like <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s magnetic
field, but rather multiple poles, researchers said.
   <PERSON>Robert Strom</PERSON> of the Voyager imaging team said the relative
scarcity of craters on <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION> tends to confirm speculation that
<ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION> originated outside the solar system and became captured by
<LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s gravity, perhaps after colliding with one of its moons.
   Voyager also revealed that <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION> has an atmosphere and is
covered with a haze of what could be photochemical smog.
   On the moon's sunlit southern hemisphere, frozen methane or other
volatile material is boiling off the surface, causing haze, and
condensing on the moon's cooler regions, scientists said.
   Voyager 2 was launched in <DATE>1977</DATE> and explored <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1979</DATE>,
<ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1981</DATE> and Uranus in <DATE>1986</DATE>. Until <DATE>Oct. 2</DATE>, Voyager 2 will look
back at <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>. Then it will head toward interstellar space.
   Weary <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> scientists, many of whom spent all night at the
laboratory analyzing data returning from the spacecraft, gushed over
the spectacular images being received.
   <PERSON>Laurence Soderblom</PERSON> of the Voyager imaging team said: ``Wow! What
a way to leave the solar system.''
</TEXT>
