<HEAD>NASA Experiment Gets Galileo to Send Venus Photos Early</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> engineers were unwilling to wait
until <DATE>October</DATE> to see the <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> spacecraft's photographs of Venus,
so they used an experimental method to get three of the pictures
sent to <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> early.
   One of the photos released <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> shows clouds as small as 25
miles wide as well as clouds rising from lower in the atmosphere.
It was taken <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> when the Jupiter-bound <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> was about
1 million miles past <PERSON>Venus</PERSON>, the second planet from the sun.
   ``You can see clouds, and you can see some very interesting
detail in the cloud patterns,'' said <PERSON>Neal Ausman</PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> mission
director at the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space Administration</ORGANIZATION>'s Jet
Propulsion Laboratory. ``The engineers and scientists are
exceptionally pleased.''
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> is scheduled to go into orbit around <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>December
1995</DATE> in a <MONEY>$1.35 billion</MONEY> mission to study the solar system's largest
planet. Just before <TIME>10 p.m. PST</TIME> <DATE>last Friday</DATE>, the spacecraft swooped
about 10,025 miles over <LOCATION>Venus</LOCATION> so that planet could act as a gravity
slingshot to help hurl the spacecraft on its way to <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>.
   Most of the photographs and other data collected during and
after the flyby won't be sent back until <DATE>October</DATE>, when the
spacecraft is closer to <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s main antenna now is furled
to protect it from the heat of the sun. A smaller antenna, which
can transmit and receive information only at a very slow rate, is
being used almost exclusively to operate the spacecraft.
   But <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> engineers were able to get <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> to send the three
photos back to <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> on <DATE>Monday</DATE> and <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> by transferring separate
batches of the computer data that make up each image for radio
transmission, <PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said.
   <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Jim Wilson</PERSON> called the technique ``experimental
and difficult.''
   <PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said engineers also were able to get the spacecraft to
send back some infrared light measurements designed to study <PERSON>Venus</PERSON>'
lower atmosphere, as well as ultraviolet light measurements and
data from sensors designed to detect dust and magnetic fields in
space around <LOCATION>Venus</LOCATION>.
   By the time <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>'s fly-by of Venus formally ends <DATE>Friday</DATE>
<TIME>night</TIME>, the spacecraft's television camera will have taken about 80
pictures of cloud-shrouded <PERSON>Venus</PERSON>.
   Many other spacecraft have photographed <PERSON>Venus</PERSON>, some from much
closer than <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION>. But the new photos still should have
scientific value, <PERSON>Ausman</PERSON> said.
   <ORGANIZATION>Galileo</ORGANIZATION> was deployed from the space shuttle Atlantis last <DATE>Oct.
18</DATE> on a looping 2.4 billion, six-year route that requires <PERSON>Venus</PERSON> and
Earth to be used as gravity slingshots to hurl the spacecraft to
<ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>. It will fly past <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> on <DATE>Dec. 8</DATE>, then again on <DATE>Dec. 8,
1992</DATE>.
   Meanwhile, in the outer reaches of the solar system, the Voyager
1 spacecraft sent radio signals indicating it had successfully
snapped photographs to make up the first group portrait of the
solar system, according to <ORGANIZATION>JPL</ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON>Mary Hardin</PERSON>.
   Voyager 1, which photographed <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1980</DATE> and <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> in
<DATE>1981</DATE>, was ordered to shoot the pictures <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> <TIME>evening</TIME>. But it
took five hours and 36 minutes for confirmation of the photographs
to travel the 3.7 billion miles to <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Hardin</PERSON> said <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
</TEXT>
