<HEAD>Neptune's Third Moon Discovered By Approaching Voyager 2 Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seeking new worlds 2.75 billion miles
from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'S Voyager 2 spacecraft discovered a third moon
orbiting <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> and is likely to find many more, scientists say.
   ``It's nice, after years of preparation for the <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>
encounter, to have Voyager now starting to make these discoveries,''
Jet Propulsion Laboratory astronomer <PERSON>Steve Synnott</PERSON> said <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
``Ninety-nine-point-nine percent of the time this discovery process
is frustration, so it is finally nice to dig a nugget out of all the
mud.''
   Synnott detected the moon, temporarily designated <DATE>1989</DATE> N1, in
photographs taken by one of the space probe's television cameras.
Previously, only two moons had been detected from earth.
   Project scientist <PERSON>Ellis Miner</PERSON> said recently that Voyager might
discover at least 10 small moons orbiting <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>.
   Voyagers 1 and 2 _ with total mission costs of <MONEY>$865 million</MONEY> _ now
have discovered at least 18 moons: three at <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, at least four
and possibly seven at <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION>, 10 orbiting Uranus, and one so far at
<LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>.
   That boosts the total lunar count to 16 for <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, at least 17
for <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION>, 15 for Uranus and three for <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Synnott</PERSON>, who helped discover several of those moons, was asked
how he celebrates when he finds an entire new world.
   ``I usually go home and have a beer,'' he said.
   The Jet Propulsion laboratory operates <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s unmanned space
exploration program for the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and Space
Administration</ORGANIZATION>.
   Voyager 2 was launched from <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> in <DATE>1977</DATE>, explored <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> in
<DATE>1979</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1981</DATE> and Uranus in <DATE>1986</DATE>. Today it was 2.67 billion
miles from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and 42.8 million miles from <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>, speeding at
42,200 mph toward its <DATE>Aug. 24</DATE> close encounter with the solar
system's fourth-largest planet.
   Voyager will be 2.75 billion miles from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> when it sweeps
3,000 miles above <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s north pole cloudtops at <TIME>midnight EDT</TIME>
<DATE>Aug. 24</DATE>, but its curving path to <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> will equal 4.43 billion
miles.
   Neptune's other moons are Nereid and the backward-orbiting
<ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION>, discovered through telescopes on <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> in <DATE>1949</DATE> and <DATE>1846</DATE>,
respectively.
   In <DATE>1981</DATE>, scientists using telescopes believed they detected
another Neptunian moon, but its existence hasn't yet been confirmed
by Voyager.
   With a diameter estimated at 125 to 400 miles, <DATE>1989</DATE> N1 is smaller
than Nereid _ estimated at 190 to 620 miles across _ or <ORGANIZATION>Triton</ORGANIZATION>, with
an estimated diameter of 1,400 to 2,240 miles, or roughly the size
of <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s moon.
   Synnott first detected the moon as a smudge in images taken by
Voyager 2 on <DATE>June 21</DATE>. He confirmed the discovery <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> by
examining images.
   ``I never really jumped and screamed, but I clenched my fist,
nodded my head to myself and said, `Yup, that one's real!''' he said.
</TEXT>
