<HEAD>Magnetic Field Around Neptune Discovered By Voyager 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Voyager 2 space probe discovered that
a magnetic field surrounds <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>, suggesting the planet is
enveloped by orbiting radiation belts and has an aurora like <ORGANIZATION>Earth</ORGANIZATION>'s
northern lights, <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> announced <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   Further study of the magnetic field should allow scientists to
determine the exact length of a day on <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>, believed to be 17 to
18 Earth hours, and to gain better understanding of <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s
internal structure, said <PERSON>Mary Beth Murrill</PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION>'s
Jet Propulsion Laboratory.
   Just as <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s magnetic field traps the Van <PERSON>Allen</PERSON> radiation
belts, <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s magnetic field also may help create radiation belts
around that planet. Scientists don't yet know if that poses a hazard
to Voyager 2's electronic components, <PERSON>Murrill</PERSON> said.
   Voyager was 2.74 billion miles from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and 5.92 million miles
from <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> on <DATE>Friday</DATE>, speeding toward the giant gas planet at
42,236 mph.
   The spacecraft was launched in <DATE>1977</DATE> and explored <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1979</DATE>,
<ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1981</DATE> and Uranus in <DATE>1986</DATE>. Voyager 2 will make its closest
approach to <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> at <TIME>8:59 p.m. PDT</TIME> on <DATE>Thursday</DATE> when it flies about
3,000 miles over the cloudtops of the solar system's fourth-largest
planet.
   Voyager already has discovered four Neptunian moons in addition
to the two discovered from <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, two partial rings, or ring arcs,
of debris orbiting the planet; and atmospheric patterns similar to
jet streams and giant cyclones on <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>.
   Discovery of <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s magnetic field was confirmed <DATE>Friday</DATE> by
intense, pulse-like radio emissions coming from the planet's
vicinity. Radio waves are generated when high-speed electrically
charged particles spiral into a planet's atmosphere along magnetic
field lines.
   ``Mercury, <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Jupiter</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Saturn</ORGANIZATION> and Uranus have magnetic
fields, while <PERSON>Venus</PERSON> and Mars do not,'' the <ORGANIZATION>National Aeronautics and
Space Administration</ORGANIZATION> said in a news release. ``Whether <LOCATION>Pluto</LOCATION> has one
or not is unknown.
   ``A planetary magnetic field is a girdle of magnetic field lines
that surround a planet,'' the agency said. ``Such fields are thought
to be generated by fluid motion in a planet's core. (<ORGANIZATION>Molten</ORGANIZATION> iron in
<LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s core, for example).''
   Certain electrically charged particles in space spiral along
magnetic field lines toward <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s poles, creating the northern and
southern lights. A magnetic field at <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> means that planet also
may have auroras, <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> said.
   Scientists hope the magnetic field will allow them to understand
<LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s internal structure. Voyager project scientist <ORGANIZATION>Edward Stone</ORGANIZATION>
has said he believes that <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s hydrogen-helium outer atmosphere
gradually gives way to a superhot slurry of hot water and rock
closer to the planet's center. That would mean that <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION> _ like
neighboring Uranus _ probably lacks a distinct sky-sea boundary.
   Some scientists believe radiation trapped by Uranus' magnetic
field bombards frozen natural gas on that planet's moons and rings
to turn them dark in color. Neptune's magnetic field may cause
similar radiation darkening of the Neptunian moons and ring arcs,
<ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> said.
   The nature of <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s radio signal allowed scientists to
determine the emissions came from a magnetic field, not from
discharges of lightning in the atmosphere, said <PERSON>James Warwick</PERSON>, head
of Voyager's radio science team.
   ``The radio emissions are very intense, very impulsive and occur
in a limited range of frequency,'' <PERSON>Warwick</PERSON>, a scientist at <LOCATION>Boulder</LOCATION>,
<ORGANIZATION>Colo.-based Radiophysics Inc.</ORGANIZATION>, said in the release.
   Once <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> confirmed the existence of <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s magnetic field
<DATE>Friday</DATE>, scientists found evidence for the telltale radio signals in
data collected by Voyager as early as <DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   ``Early analysis indicates <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s magnetic field is of an
intensity similar to the fields of <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> and Uranus,'' <ORGANIZATION>NASA</ORGANIZATION> said.
   <PERSON>Murrill</PERSON> said scientists don't yet know how <LOCATION>Neptune</LOCATION>'s magnetic
field is aligned. Voyager found the axis of Uranus' magnetic field
was tilted about 60 degrees from the axis around which that planet
spins.
   Earth's north magnetic pole is tilted about 14 degrees from the
planet's north rotational axis.
</TEXT>
